INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5593841e-ae91-4062-9e15-0e3212fa61da',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$OpenAI API — Tokens, Context Windows, and Sampling Parameters Demystified$escape$,
  $escape$Every OpenAI API call operates on tokens, not characters. GPT-4o supports a 128k-token context window — input + output combined. Exceed it and you get a 400 error. Use tiktoken to count tokens before sending: cl100k_base for GPT-4/3.5, o200k_base for GPT-4o.

Temperature (0–2) controls output randomness. At 0, the model is nearly deterministic — greedy-decoding the highest-probability token each step. At 1, it samples proportionally. At 2, outputs get chaotic. For code generation, use 0–0.2. For creative tasks, 0.7–1.0.

top_p is nucleus sampling: the model only considers tokens whose cumulative probability mass reaches top_p. Set top_p=0.1 to restrict to the top 10% of the distribution — tighter than temperature alone. OpenAI recommends altering temperature OR top_p, not both simultaneously.

max_completion_tokens caps output length independently of context. Use it to enforce response budgets. Combine with stream=True to surface tokens as they're generated, reducing perceived latency on long completions.$escape$,
  $escape$import tiktoken
from openai import OpenAI

client = OpenAI()
enc = tiktoken.get_encoding("o200k_base")  # GPT-4o encoding

messages = [{"role": "user", "content": "Explain backpressure in 3 sentences."}]
token_count = sum(len(enc.encode(m["content"])) for m in messages)
print(f"Input tokens: {token_count}")

response = client.chat.completions.create(
    model="gpt-4o",
    messages=messages,
    temperature=0.3,
    top_p=1.0,
    max_completion_tokens=120,
)
print(response.choices[0].message.content)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
